      Poison pills
   =20
 =20
Here are some things you could do[1]:=09Buy 51% of the stock of a public co=
mpany in the open market over time, just buying whenever anyone sells, look=
ing for any blocks of stock that come loose, paying the market price for ea=
ch trade, etc. To put numbers on it, let=E2=80=99s say you start buying at =
around $40 per share and finish at around $50 per share. (Your buying, and =
the legally required disclosure of your ownership, will push up the price.)=
 Once you have 51%, you take control, vote out the board, vote in your budd=
ies, elect a new chief executive officer and run the company however you wa=
nt.=09Buy 51% of the stock of a public company in a tender offer. A tender =
offer is just a big coordinated public offer to buy stock, open=C2=A0to all=
 shareholders at the same price.=C2=A0You announce to all shareholders, =E2=
=80=9CI want to buy 51% of this company and I=E2=80=99ll pay $50 per share =
in cash, but I won=E2=80=99t buy more than 51%.=E2=80=9D More than 51% tend=
er, you prorate the offer (not buying all the shares that are tendered), yo=
u get to exactly 51%, paying $50 per share. You proceed as above, taking co=
ntrol of the board etc.=09You acquire 51% of the company and take control o=
f the board, as in either Thing 1 or Thing 2. Then you propose a merger at =
$30 per share. The new board =E2=80=94=C2=A0your buddies =E2=80=94=C2=A0agr=
ees, and submits it to a shareholder vote. You vote your 51% of the shares =
in favor, and the merger happens; you acquire the remaining 49% of the stoc=
k at $30 per share. The holders of that 49% =E2=80=94=C2=A0who did not sell=
 to you at $50 in the first step =E2=80=94=C2=A0are forced to sell to you a=
t $30 in the second step. (That=E2=80=99s how mergers work: When the merger=
 happens, the stock is automatically converted into whatever the merger con=
sideration is, here $30 in cash.)=09Same as Thing 1, but instead of buying =
51% you buy, I don=E2=80=99t know, 30%. At 30% you just need to convince a =
few other shareholders to vote with you to kick out the board, etc. As the =
biggest shareholder, you might have effective control even without a majori=
ty.=09Offer to buy 100% of the stock of the company in a tender offer. Anno=
unce to all shareholders, =E2=80=9CI want to buy 100% of this company and I=
=E2=80=99ll pay $50 per share in cash. But let me warn you. If I get above =
51%, but not to 100%, I will definitely do a second-step merger (as in Thin=
g 3), and I=E2=80=99ll do it at $30 per share. So if you want $50, you bett=
er tender now, because if you don=E2=80=99t you=E2=80=99re getting $30.=E2=
=80=9D Shareholders might think that $50 is too low, and might not want to =
tender. But they can=E2=80=99t be sure that 51% of the stock=C2=A0won=E2=80=
=99t=C2=A0tender, and they don=E2=80=99t want to be left out. So they tende=
r for $50 to avoid getting stuck with $30. (This is called a =E2=80=9Ctwo-t=
ier tender offer.=E2=80=9D)=09Same as Thing 5 but you don=E2=80=99t make th=
e threat explicit. =E2=80=9CI want to buy 100% of this company and I=E2=80=
=99ll pay $50 per share in cash,=E2=80=9D you say. But you have a reputatio=
n for being tough, and a history of treating minority shareholders poorly. =
The threat is implicit, so shareholders tender at $50 to avoid ending up=C2=
=A0in the minority of a company that you control.These are the things, the =
classic things.=C2=A0They are =E2=80=9Ccoercive takeover tactics,=E2=80=9D =
in the lingo. They are ways for someone =E2=80=94=C2=A0a =E2=80=9Ccorporate=
 raider,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0in the lingo =E2=80=94=C2=A0to take over a company w=
ithout paying a fair price for it, or without offering every shareholder th=
e same price. Or, I mean, arguably=C2=A0without paying a fair price; you mi=
ght think that some of these things are fine. (If you can get 51% of the sh=
areholders of a company to sell you their stock in market transactions, wha=
t=E2=80=99s the problem?) But boards of directors of public companies gener=
ally take a dim view of these things. They think of themselves as fiduciari=
es for all of the shareholders, and they do not like the idea of someone bu=
ying the company out from under them.=C2=A0Instead, the board of directors =
will prefer a nice tidy negotiation between the buyer and the board. The bu=
yer comes to the board and offers a merger, and they negotiate the terms wi=
th each other. If the board agrees to a deal, it will generally involve the=
 buyer paying the same price to every shareholder, and it will be a price t=
hat the board thinks reflects the full=C2=A0value of the company. Once the =
buyer has an agreement with the board, they will go out together, buyer and=
 board, and seek shareholder approval. (Either by signing a merger agreemen=
t and submitting it to a shareholder vote, or by doing a tender offer in wh=
ich the buyer asks to buy all the shares from shareholders=C2=A0directly, b=
ut on terms approved by the board.) If the board does not agree to the deal=
, the buyer goes away peacefully and does not cause trouble by buying more =
stock, launching a tender offer to shareholders without board approval, or =
running a proxy fight in which the buyer tries to replace the board with it=
s own nominees. That is the dignified, controlled way that corporate boards=
 generally prefer to do mergers-and-acquisitions negotiations.Many buyers l=
ike to do M&A this way too. (If you are taking over a company, it helps to =
be friendly with the people running the company! You=E2=80=99ll need them t=
o help you run the company!) But some buyers =E2=80=94=C2=A0the corporate r=
aiders, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0like to retain the ability to go hostile, to do=
 unsolicited tender offers or proxy fights if the board rejects their offer=
s. For one thing, sometimes boards are unreasonable, and going directly to =
the shareholders is the only way to get a deal done. For another thing, the=
=C2=A0threat=C2=A0of going hostile can be helpful in negotiations with the =
board.In the U.S., the board has a powerful tool in this fight. It is=C2=A0=
the poison pill.=C2=A0(Everyone calls it that, though its technical legal n=
ame is a =E2=80=9Cshareholder rights plan.=E2=80=9D) The board of directors=
 of a company, feeling threatened=C2=A0by a big acquirer of its=C2=A0stock =
or a corporate raider proposing to buy the company, will adopt a =E2=80=9Cs=
hareholder rights plan.=E2=80=9D The gist of the plan is that if anyone =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0meaning, basically, the buyer =E2=80=94=C2=A0acquires more than=
 X% of the company=E2=80=99s stock (often X is 15 or 20), then that person=
=E2=80=99s shares go poof. You can=E2=80=99t actually do that =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0you can=E2=80=99t make one shareholder=E2=80=99s shares go poof =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0but you can get arbitrarily close by allowing all of the=C2=A0othe=
r shareholders of the company to buy many=C2=A0more=C2=A0shares at a discou=
nt, or by giving them more shares for free. So you say =E2=80=9Cif anyone g=
oes above 15% of the stock, then we will distribute one free share of stock=
 for each existing share,=C2=A0except=C2=A0that the person who went above 1=
5% doesn=E2=80=99t get any of the free stock.=E2=80=9D So if someone gets 1=
5%, then everyone=C2=A0else=E2=80=99s shares get doubled, taking the acquir=
er down to about 8%.[2] (In theory you could do this repeatedly, so that th=
e acquirer could=C2=A0never=C2=A0get a controlling stake.)The actual mechan=
ics are a bit more complicated than that, but not worth worrying about[3]; =
even the summary in the previous paragraph=C2=A0is not worth worrying about=
. The point is that the pill makes it very bad for anyone to get above 15% =
of the stock =E2=80=94=C2=A0it basically makes their stock go poof =E2=80=
=94 so nobody does. For a long time it was common to say that a poison pill=
 had never been triggered;=C2=A0that is not quite true anymore, but it is s=
till close enough. When a board adopts a poison pill, for all practical pur=
poses that prevents a buyer from buying more than 15% of the=C2=A0stock, ei=
ther in the open market or in a tender offer. So it forces the buyer to neg=
otiate with the board. If the buyer wants to buy the company, it has to str=
ike a deal with the board (which will then get rid of the pill); it can=E2=
=80=99t just go directly to the shareholders to buy stock, because the pill=
 will make its shares go poof.(Some disclosure: The poison pill was invente=
d by the law firm of Wachtell, Lipton, Rosen & Katz, where I worked briefly=
 in the mid-2000s. In my discussion of takeover defenses and tactics, I am =
drawing on Wachtell=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CTakeover Law and Practice=E2=80=9D g=
uide, which is worth reading if you want more detail on how this all works.=
 But I worked there a long time ago and any errors or oversimplifications h=
ere are not the firm=E2=80=99s fault.)The poison pill is a bizarre and dras=
tic thing for a board to do =E2=80=94=C2=A0to make one shareholder=E2=80=99=
s stock go poof! =E2=80=94=C2=A0and when it was invented in the 1980s there=
 was some skepticism that it was legal. But the Delaware Supreme Court=C2=
=A0approved it, in a 1985 decision, noting that the board=E2=80=99s reason =
for=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthe adoption of the Rights Plan was in reaction to what i=
t perceived to be the threat in the market place of coercive two-tier tende=
r offers=E2=80=9D (my Thing 5 above). Basically the idea was that (1) corpo=
rate raiders sometimes do bad coercive things to take over companies, (2) b=
oards have a fiduciary duty to=C2=A0stop them and (3) drastic measures, lik=
e the poison pill, are justified to stop coercive takeover tactics.But the =
pill quickly became a standard feature of corporate defense even against no=
t-very-coercive actions. Boards of directors have successfully used poison =
pills to block non-coercive, all-shares-at-the-same-price tender offers, an=
d to put limits on activists=E2=80=99 ability to run=C2=A0proxy fights. The=
 broad general rule is that the board gets to decide on takeovers, and that=
 if it acts in good faith to prevent a change of control, it can, even if s=
hareholders would prefer to take the money.So what does this have to do wit=
h Elon Musk.This weekend, Twitter Inc.=E2=80=99s board=C2=A0 adopted a pois=
on pill to protect itself against Elon Musk=E2=80=99s  plan to maybe acquir=
e the company. You can read Twitter=E2=80=99s press release here; here is a=
 more detailed summary of the pill, and here and here are the actual legal =
documents. The main mechanism of the pill is that if Musk or anyone else ac=
quires more than 15% of Twitter's stock, then every=C2=A0other=C2=A0Twitter=
 shareholder will have the right to pay $210 to acquire $420 worth of Twitt=
er stock (at then-current market prices). 420 IS A WEED JOKE. Otherwise the=
se numbers are sort of arbitrary =E2=80=94=C2=A0again, pills don=E2=80=99t =
get triggered, so the particular numbers don=E2=80=99t matter=C2=A0=E2=80=
=94=C2=A0and I imagine the conversation went like this:Lawyer: The pill wil=
l be structured to let other shareholders buy a large amount of stock at a =
discount to dilute Musk=E2=80=99s stake.Twitter: How much stock?Lawyer: It =
doesn=E2=80=99t really matter, but=C2=A0a lot, enough to swamp Musk. Typica=
lly the exercise price would be=C2=A0like $100 to $200, and you=E2=80=99d g=
et twice as much stock, like, $200 to $400 worth.Twitter: We are defending =
against Elon Musk here and ordinary tactics are not enough. We need to harn=
ess the power of the number 420.=C2=A0Lawyer: Okay then $420 worth of stock=
, whatever.Another, perhaps more practical=C2=A0provision of the pill says =
that the board can just exchange each right for one share of stock, for fre=
e, meaning in essence that the board can double everyone else=E2=80=99s num=
ber of shares of Twitter while holding Musk=E2=80=99s constant, without ask=
ing anyone to put in more money.=C2=A0This weekend, Musk tweeted =E2=80=9CL=
ove Me Tender.=E2=80=9D Because he is engaged in an annoying meme-driven ma=
ybe-hostile-takeover-battle, everyone interpreted this to mean something li=
ke =E2=80=9Cmaybe I will do a tender offer for Twitter, or maybe not, who k=
nows, aren=E2=80=99t I a little scamp.=E2=80=9D With the pill in place, he =
more or less can=E2=80=99t. He has to negotiate with the board, or run a pr=
oxy fight to replace the board,[4] or get other shareholders to pressure th=
e board to get rid of the pill, or I suppose sue the board to get rid of th=
e pill.There is a popular belief that, since Musk offered a cash acquisitio=
n at a price that is a decent premium to the market price, the board is som=
ehow either obligated to accept his deal or at least obligated to let the s=
hareholders decide.[5] This is wrong. The board gets to decide. From Wachte=
ll=E2=80=99s takeover guide:It seems clear that the target may, if it meets=
 the relevant standard, =E2=80=9Cjust say no=E2=80=9D to an acquisition pro=
posal.=C2=A0Targets of unsolicited offers have been successful in rejecting=
 such proposals in order to follow their own strategic plans. =E2=80=A6Whil=
e a rights plan [i.e. poison pill]=C2=A0is often the most useful tool for s=
taving off a hostile bid, it is not necessary to successfully =E2=80=9Cjust=
 say no=E2=80=9D in every situation. What is typically necessary=E2=80=94an=
d what a rights plan is designed to protect=E2=80=94is a thoughtful long-te=
rm plan that was developed by a board and management whom long-term shareho=
lders trust to deliver value.The basic legal rule here is=C2=A0the =E2=80=
=9Cbusiness judgment rule,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0which is that the board of directo=
rs runs the company and courts do not generally second-guess their decision=
s if they are made carefully and in good faith. If Twitter=E2=80=99s board =
is advised by good bankers and lawyers, has no serious conflicts of interes=
t,=C2=A0takes Musk=E2=80=99s offer seriously, and concludes that keeping Tw=
itter independent and executing its strategic plan will be worth more to sh=
areholders than Musk=E2=80=99s $54.20, then it can decline Musk=E2=80=99s o=
ffer.There are other relevant rules. One is that, if the board=C2=A0does=C2=
=A0decide to sell the company for cash, it needs to maximize value for shar=
eholders. This is called the board=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9CRevlon duty,=E2=80=9D=
 but it is=C2=A0pretty limited. It does=C2=A0not=C2=A0mean that the board h=
as to sell to Musk if his offer is higher than the current stock price. It =
just means that, if=C2=A0the board decides to sell for cash, it needs to ma=
ximize value.[6] But even if the board does decide to sell, it could concei=
vably take another offer at a=C2=A0lower price than Musk=E2=80=99s bid, if =
either (1) the other deal is for=C2=A0stock, whose valuation is more subjec=
tive=C2=A0or (2) the other deal is, in the board=E2=80=99s judgment, more l=
ikely to be completed, for instance because it has actual financing and Mus=
k=E2=80=99s doesn=E2=80=99t really.Another relevant rule is that, if the bo=
ard says no, any defensive measures it puts in place have to be reasonable.=
 This is called the =E2=80=9CUnocal standard.=E2=80=9D The board needs to s=
how that it has =E2=80=9Creasonable grounds for believing that a danger to =
corporate policy and effectiveness existed,=E2=80=9D and that its defensive=
 measures were =E2=80=9Creasonable in relation to the threat posed.=E2=80=
=9D This is also not that high a bar, though: The poison pill is a fairly s=
tandard defensive measure at this point, and the board=E2=80=99s conclusion=
 that a takeover price is =E2=80=9Cinadequate=E2=80=9D is generally enough =
of a threat.Why would Twitter's=C2=A0board of directors want to stop Elon M=
usk? There is one main reason, which is that they (might) believe, in good =
faith, that the company is worth more than the $54.20 per share that he has=
 offered to pay for it. This is of course a debatable point. Twitter was tr=
ading in the $70s last summer, so there is some recent evidence that it mig=
ht be worth more than $54.20. But in the weeks before Musk built his stake,=
 it was trading in the $30s, so the market no longer believes that. Twitter=
=E2=80=99s own performance is what caused the price decline, and it is not =
obvious that it will turn around soon.Awkwardly, Twitter=E2=80=99s own advi=
ser, Goldman Sachs Group Inc. (disclosure: I also used to work there) put a=
 $30 price target on Twitter in February. (Twitter has also  hired JPMorgan=
; Bloomberg tells me its most recent price target is $56.)=C2=A0I know this=
 because Musk tweeted out the research report. Goldman=E2=80=99s research a=
nalysts, who put out this price target, are pretty independent from its inv=
estment bankers, who are advising Twitter, and there=E2=80=99s no reason th=
at the bankers could not find the $54.20 price inadequate even as the analy=
sts think Twitter would be lucky to get $30. But it is the sort of thing th=
at Musk rightly makes fun of. Still, enough  shareholders and analysts seem=
 to think that $54.20 is inadequate that Twitter=E2=80=99s board, in its in=
dependent business judgment, could conclude the same thing.=C2=A0And so the=
 board put in place a poison pill to stop Musk from going directly to the s=
hareholders with his $54.20 bid. Maybe now Musk and the board will negotiat=
e a higher price, perhaps $69. Or maybe now the board will find a higher bi=
dder. Or maybe not; maybe the board will just say no to Musk and that will =
be that. It is not the most=C2=A0common=C2=A0result in these situations, ju=
st because then the stock would probably go back down, at least in the shor=
t run, and shareholders would be mad. But it is a thing that the board can =
do, and that a court generally won=E2=80=99t second-guess.But I also want t=
o spend some time on=C2=A0other=C2=A0reasons that a board of directors migh=
t want to stop Elon Musk, reasons in the general =E2=80=9Ccoercive takeover=
 tactics=E2=80=9D bucket. Let me just list a few things that the board=E2=
=80=99s lawyers might say if this poison pill ever gets litigated.First, Mu=
sk=C2=A0did=C2=A0acquire 9.1% of the company secretly, in the open market, =
paying prices in the high $30s to get a start on his takeover without payin=
g a control premium. Crucially, he seems to have done some of this acquirin=
g=C2=A0illegally:=C2=A0He was required by law to disclose his ownership sta=
ke, and probably his intention to take over the company, by March 24, but h=
e waited until April 4 to make that disclosure, and claimed to be a passive=
 investor when he finally did. This delay allowed him to buy an extra 13 mi=
llion shares at lower prices,  saving him (and costing shareholders)=C2=A0o=
n the order of $140 million.The consensus seems to be that the U.S. Securit=
ies and Exchange Commission can=E2=80=99t do much about this, and while the=
re is a shareholder lawsuit about it already, it=E2=80=99s not clear that t=
hat will accomplish much either. Sometimes companies will ask courts to =E2=
=80=9Csterilize=E2=80=9D an acquirer=E2=80=99s shares, preventing him from =
voting them, if he acquired them in violation of the disclosure rules, but =
those requests don=E2=80=99t have much success. Basically Musk seems to hav=
e broken the law to buy his shares, but=C2=A0no one can do much about it.Bu=
t Twitter can stop him from buying=C2=A0more=C2=A0stock secretly, by implem=
enting the pill. It can=C2=A0reasonably argue=C2=A0that it is protecting sh=
areholders from being tricked by illegal secret stock accumulation, and tha=
t Musk has already demonstrated that he is willing to do illegal secret sto=
ck accumulation.=C2=A0Second, Musk has arguably made at least one coercive =
threat: He has said, in his public communications to the board, that if he =
can=E2=80=99t buy Twitter at $54.20 he will dump his 9.1% stake, driving do=
wn the stock price. This does not strike me as a particularly bad coercive =
threat =E2=80=94=C2=A0it doesn=E2=80=99t really leave Twitter worse off tha=
n it was before he arrived =E2=80=94=C2=A0but Tulane law professor Ann Lipt=
on argued on Twitter=C2=A0that =E2=80=9Cshareholders asked to vote or tende=
r on this offer would be doing so under threat, which the Board is legally =
entitled to protect against,=E2=80=9D and I think it is certainly an argume=
nt that the board could make.Third, Musk has said that he wants to buy all =
of Twitter at $54.20 per share. But he has also implied that he=C2=A0doesn=
=E2=80=99t. At a conference last week, Musk  said that he intends =E2=80=9C=
to retain as many shareholders as is allowed by the law in a private compan=
y.=E2=80=9D It is not at all clear what he means by that, or how seriously =
he means it. But it is reminiscent of what he said when he briefly pretende=
d he was going to take Tesla Inc. private: He wanted to allow Tesla=E2=80=
=99s existing public shareholders to roll over into the private company. (I=
t was not clear then either what he meant.) And, crucially,=C2=A0 that was =
part of his financing plan:=C2=A0He claimed that his takeover of Tesla woul=
d not require the full amount of cash to buy out all the shares, because he=
 assumed a lot of public shareholders would roll over.The financing for Mus=
k=E2=80=99s Twitter bid  is also murky, and I suppose it might rely on the =
same sort of vague wishful assumption that a lot of shareholders will roll =
over. Musk will need about $40 billion to buy out all of Twitter=E2=80=99s =
shares that he does not already own, but what if his plan is to spend, say,=
 $25 billion, and to assume that holders of the other $15 billion will roll=
 their stock over into a new Twitter, controlled by Elon Musk?If he negotia=
tes a merger with the board, then the board can insist on protections for t=
he shareholders: It can require that shareholders be given a choice of cash=
 or stock, that there be enough funding for everyone to elect cash, that th=
e shareholders=C2=A0get full disclosure before electing, etc. Maybe some sh=
areholders will want to roll their shares into Musk Twitter.But if Musk lau=
nches a hostile tender offer=C2=A0without negotiating with the board, he mi=
ght try to finesse this point. He might offer to buy, you know, 75% of the =
company or whatever, saying =E2=80=9CI am confident that a lot of sharehold=
ers will want to keep their shares so I am not offering to buy it all.=E2=
=80=9D You might end up in coercive-takeover territory, where some sharehol=
ders want to cash out but can=E2=80=99t, or where some shareholders rush to=
 cash out because they fear getting stuck with stock in a Musk-controlled T=
witter.[7] This would be pretty weird, and I do not think it is particularl=
y likely, but it is a possibility given his history and his statements and =
his caginess about his financing. And I could see Twitter=E2=80=99s board j=
ustifying the pill on these grounds too, as a way to prevent Musk from buyi=
ng less than all of Twitter on the cheap.Anyway this Wednesday is April 20,=
 that is, 4/20, the holiest day of the year for people who can=E2=80=99t st=
op making=C2=A0weed jokes, like Musk and, now, Twitter. I assume that on We=
dnesday morning either they will sign a friendly deal, or Musk will launch =
his tender offer (despite the pill!?). Otherwise they=E2=80=99ll have to wa=
it until June 9.Elsewhere in all this:=09At FT Alphaville,  Sujeet Indap bu=
ilt an LBO model suggesting that there=E2=80=99s a way for a Twitter acquis=
ition to work out.=09At the Diff,  Byrne Hobart has some strategic suggesti=
