</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are some things you could do[1]:<=
/p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px =
0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Buy 51% of the stock of a public c=
ompany in the open market over time, just buying whenever anyone sells, loo=
king for any blocks of stock that come loose, paying the market price for e=
ach trade, etc. To put numbers on it, let=E2=80=99s say you start buying at=
 around $40 per share and finish at around $50 per share. (Your buying, and=
 the legally required disclosure of your ownership, will push up the price.=
) Once you have 51%, you take control, vote out the board, vote in your bud=
dies, elect a new chief executive officer and run the company however you w=
ant.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Buy 51% of the stock of a pub=
lic company in a tender offer. A tender offer is just a big coordinated pub=
lic offer to buy stock, open=C2=A0to all shareholders at the same price.=C2=
=A0You announce to all shareholders, =E2=80=9CI want to buy 51% of this com=
pany and I=E2=80=99ll pay $50 per share in cash, but I won=E2=80=99t buy mo=
re than 51%.=E2=80=9D More than 51% tender, you prorate the offer (not buyi=
ng all the shares that are tendered), you get to exactly 51%, paying $50 pe=
r share. You proceed as above, taking control of the board etc.</li>=09<li =
style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You acquire 51% of the company and take contr=
ol of the board, as in either Thing 1 or Thing 2. Then you propose a merger=
 at $30 per share. The new board =E2=80=94=C2=A0your buddies =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0agrees, and submits it to a shareholder vote. You vote your 51% of the s=
hares in favor, and the merger happens; you acquire the remaining 49% of th=
e stock at $30 per share. The holders of that 49% =E2=80=94=C2=A0who did no=
t sell to you at $50 in the first step =E2=80=94=C2=A0are forced to sell to=
 you at $30 in the second step. (That=E2=80=99s how mergers work: When the =
merger happens, the stock is automatically converted into whatever the merg=
er consideration is, here $30 in cash.)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">Same as Thing 1, but instead of buying 51% you buy, I don=E2=80=99t k=
now, 30%. At 30% you just need to convince a few other shareholders to vote=
 with you to kick out the board, etc. As the biggest shareholder, you might=
 have effective control even without a majority.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin=
-bottom: 5px;">Offer to buy 100% of the stock of the company in a tender of=
fer. Announce to all shareholders, =E2=80=9CI want to buy 100% of this comp=
any and I=E2=80=99ll pay $50 per share in cash. But let me warn you. If I g=
et above 51%, but not to 100%, I will definitely do a second-step merger (a=
s in Thing 3), and I=E2=80=99ll do it at $30 per share. So if you want $50,=
 you better tender now, because if you don=E2=80=99t you=E2=80=99re getting=
 $30.=E2=80=9D Shareholders might think that $50 is too low, and might not =
want to tender. But they can=E2=80=99t be sure that 51% of the stock=C2=A0<=
em>won=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>tender, and they don=E2=80=99t want to be left o=
ut. So they tender for $50 to avoid getting stuck with $30. (This is called=
 a =E2=80=9C<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/274078=
97.282598/aHR0cHM6Ly9lbi53aWtpcGVkaWEub3JnL3dpa2kvVW5vY2FsX0NvcnAuX3YuX01lc=
2FfUGV0cm9sZXVtX0NvLg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd082aa10" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">two-tier t=
ender offer</a>.=E2=80=9D)</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Same as=
 Thing 5 but you don=E2=80=99t make the threat explicit. =E2=80=9CI want to=
 buy 100% of this company and I=E2=80=99ll pay $50 per share in cash,=E2=80=
=9D you say. But you have a reputation for being tough, and a history of tr=
eating minority shareholders poorly. The threat is implicit, so shareholder=
s tender at $50 to avoid ending up=C2=A0in the minority of a company that y=
ou control.</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">These are the things, the=
 classic things.=C2=A0They are =E2=80=9Ccoercive takeover tactics,=E2=80=9D=
 in the lingo. They are ways for someone =E2=80=94=C2=A0a =E2=80=9Ccorporat=
e raider,=E2=80=9D=C2=A0in the lingo =E2=80=94=C2=A0to take over a company =
without paying a fair price for it, or without offering every shareholder t=
he same price. Or, I mean, <em>arguably=C2=A0</em>without paying a fair pri=
ce; you might think that some of these things are fine. (If you can get 51%=
 of the shareholders of a company to sell you their stock in market transac=
tions, what=E2=80=99s the problem?) But boards of directors of public compa=
nies generally take a dim view of these things. They think of themselves as=
 fiduciaries for all of the shareholders, and they do not like the idea of =
someone buying the company out from under them.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin=
: 16px 0;">Instead, the board of directors will prefer a nice tidy negotiat=
ion between the buyer and the board. The buyer comes to the board and offer=
s a merger, and they negotiate the terms with each other. If the board agre=
es to a deal, it will generally involve the buyer paying the same price to =
every shareholder, and it will be a price that the board thinks reflects th=
e full=C2=A0value of the company. Once the buyer has an agreement with the =
board, they will go out together, buyer and board, and seek shareholder app=
roval. (Either by signing a merger agreement and submitting it to a shareho=
lder vote, or by doing a tender offer in which the buyer asks to buy all th=
e shares from shareholders=C2=A0directly, but on terms approved by the boar=
d.) If the board does not agree to the deal, the buyer goes away peacefully=
 and does not cause trouble by buying more stock, launching a tender offer =
to shareholders without board approval, or running a proxy fight in which t=
he buyer tries to replace the board with its own nominees. That is the dign=
ified, controlled way that corporate boards generally prefer to do mergers-=
and-acquisitions negotiations.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Many buyers =
like to do M&amp;A this way too. (If you are taking over a company, it help=
s to be friendly with the people running the company! You=E2=80=99ll need t=
hem to help you run the company!) But some buyers =E2=80=94=C2=A0the corpor=
ate raiders, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0like to retain the ability to go hostile, =
to do unsolicited tender offers or proxy fights if the board rejects their =
offers. For one thing, sometimes boards are unreasonable, and going directl=
y to the shareholders is the only way to get a deal done. For another thing=
, the=C2=A0<em>threat=C2=A0</em>of going hostile can be helpful in negotiat=
ions with the board.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In the U.S., the board=
 has a powerful tool in this fight. It is=C2=A0the poison pill.=C2=A0(Every=
one calls it that, though its technical legal name is a =E2=80=9Cshareholde=
r rights plan.=E2=80=9D) The board of directors of a company, feeling threa=
tened=C2=A0by a big acquirer of its=C2=A0stock or a corporate raider propos=
ing to buy the company, will adopt a =E2=80=9Cshareholder rights plan.=E2=
=80=9D The gist of the plan is that if anyone =E2=80=94=C2=A0meaning, basic=
ally, the buyer =E2=80=94=C2=A0acquires more than X% of the company=E2=80=
=99s stock (often X is 15 or 20), then that person=E2=80=99s shares go poof=
. You can=E2=80=99t actually do that =E2=80=94=C2=A0you can=E2=80=99t make =
one shareholder=E2=80=99s shares go poof =E2=80=94=C2=A0but you can get arb=
itrarily close by allowing all of the=C2=A0<em>other </em>shareholders of t=
he company to buy many=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>shares at a discount, or by =
giving them more shares for free. So you say =E2=80=9Cif anyone goes above =
15% of the stock, then we will distribute one free share of stock for each =
existing share,=C2=A0<em>except=C2=A0</em>that the person who went above 15=
% doesn=E2=80=99t get any of the free stock.=E2=80=9D So if someone gets 15=
%, then everyone=C2=A0<em>else</em>=E2=80=99s shares get doubled, taking th=
e acquirer down to about 8%.[2] (In theory you could do this repeatedly, so=
 that the acquirer could=C2=A0<em>never=C2=A0</em>get a controlling stake.)=
</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The actual mechanics are a bit more compli=
cated than that, but not worth worrying about[3]; even the summary in the p=
revious paragraph=C2=A0is not worth worrying about. The point is that the p=
ill makes it very bad for anyone to get above 15% of the stock =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0it basically makes their stock go poof =E2=80=94 so nobody does. For a l=
ong time it was common to say that a poison pill had never been triggered;=
