, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Meanwhile in crypto</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here=E2=80=99s a trade you can=E2=80=
=99t do:</p><ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; marg=
in: 16px 0;">=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Find a small publicly tra=
ded bank. Say it=E2=80=99s a bank with $10 billion of assets, with an equit=
y market capitalization of $1 billion. (These are realistic numbers; the ma=
rket value of a bank=E2=80=99s stock will generally be much lower than the =
value of its assets, because most of those assets are in effect owed to its=
 depositors.[8])</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Buy 51% of the st=
ock for $510 million or whatever.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: =
5px;">Vote out the board, vote in a new board and=C2=A0make yourself the ch=
ief executive officer.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Take the $1=
0 billion in the vault and send it to yourself, making $10 billion on your =
$510 million investment.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Smirk =E2=
=80=9Cwhat, I own the bank, I take the money,=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s how it wo=
rks.=E2=80=9D</li></ol><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That=E2=80=99s not how =
it works,=C2=A0you can=E2=80=99t do this,[9] if you did do it you would go =
to prison, but you=E2=80=99d be stopped well before that point. But in its =
outlines it is a tempting and elegant=C2=A0trade, and we have <a href=3D"ht=
tps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27407897.282598/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3c=
uYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTktMDMtMDEvaW5zdXJhbmNlLWlzLX=
doZXJlLXRoZS1tb25leS1pcz9jbXBpZD1CQkQwNDE4MjJfTU9ORVlTVFVGRiZ1dG1fbWVkaXVtP=
WVtYWlsJnV0bV9zb3VyY2U9bmV3c2xldHRlciZ1dG1fdGVybT0yMjA0MTgmdXRtX2NhbXBhaWdu=
PW1vbmV5c3R1ZmY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB01dcc07c" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> talked about va=
riations</a>=C2=A0that work a little better. (The guy we talked about=C2=A0=
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27407897.282598/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9pbnN1cmFuY2UtZXhlY3V0aXZlLWdyZWctbGluZ=
GJlcmctc2VudGVuY2VkLXRvLXNldmVuLXllYXJzLWFuZC10aHJlZS1tb250aHMtaW4tcHJpc29u=
LTExNTk3ODc3MzY3/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBd8ac13e7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" =
itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"><em>did=C2=A0</=
em>go to prison</a>, though he did get the money first, so his version work=
ed only a little better.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The basic idea of=
 the trade is that there exist in the world some very large=C2=A0pots of mo=
ney =E2=80=94=C2=A0banks, insurance companies, asset managers, etc. =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0that are=C2=A0<em>controlled=C2=A0</em>by relatively small<em>=C2=
=A0companies</em>. It takes a smaller amount of money to buy control of the=
=C2=A0company, and then you get to decide what to do with the larger pot of=
 money that the company manages. In the world of traditional finance, this =
is a well-known problem, and those pots of money tend to be very carefully =
regulated to guard against some opportunist taking control of them on the c=
heap and draining the money from the pot.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I=
n crypto, etc. etc. etc. etc. etc. you know how this is gonna go. Here=E2=
=80=99s <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/27407897.2=
82598/aHR0cHM6Ly90d2l0dGVyLmNvbS9hbnRob255bGVlemhhbmcvc3RhdHVzLzE1MTU3MDIyN=
zYzOTYxMzAzMDc_cz0yMSZ0PU5Qb0FVbDJnMVRPc0pNWHRPUW5UNVE/607f07ceef4b8524a319=
a23cBf5232c92" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_bl=
ank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; ba=
ckground-color: #ccc;">Anthony Lee Zhang on Twitter</a>:</p><blockquote><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Beanstalk, a moderately popular new algo-stable p=
rotocol, just got attacked for $80M</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This on=
e is a very interesting hack: rather than exploit a bug in the code, it was=
 a "governance attack". My understanding is that holders of beanstalk equit=
y token holders can vote on changes to the protocol: literally, chunks of c=
ode that are added to the protocol</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way =
an algo-stable works, there's an equity layer and a debt (stablecoins) laye=
r, and possibly a bunch of reserves, so the equity layer effectively has co=
ntrol over a bunch of "stuff" that the protocol owns</p><p style=3D"margin:=
 16px 0;">Hence, a fairly simple attack:</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">1.=
 Propose a piece of code to the protocol that says "send the entire treasur=
y to my address A"<br />2. Buy a bunch of equity tokens and vote the change=
 in<br />3. Send the entire treasury to your address A</p></blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloomberg=
business.com/click/27407897.282598/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY29pbmRlc2suY29tL3RlY2gv=
MjAyMi8wNC8xNy9hdHRhY2tlci1kcmFpbnMtMTgybS1mcm9tLWJlYW5zdGFsay1zdGFibGVjb2l=
uLXByb3RvY29sLw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbc60bbad" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">CoinDesk=E2=80=
=99s summary</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The attacker =
took out a flash loan on lending platform Aave which enabled them to amass =
a large amount of Beanstalk=E2=80=99s native governance token, Stalk. With =
the voting power granted by these Stalk tokens, the attacker was able to qu=
ickly pass a malicious governance proposal that drained all protocol funds =
into a private Ethereum wallet.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;=
">Various crypto pots of money are controlled by governance tokens, and the=
 market capitalization of the governance token is often a lot lower than th=
e value in the pot, for basically the same reasons that the market capitali=
zation of a bank is generally much lower than the value of the bank=E2=80=
=99s assets. And the governance token can, by majority vote, decide what to=
 do with the pot. (Sometimes =E2=80=94=C2=A0many pots are better designed t=
han this!) And in crypto, you can often do a series of transactions as a si=
ngle integrated=C2=A0transaction, in which you take out a flash loan to buy=
 all the governance tokens, vote the governance tokens to give yourself the=
 pot of money, use some of the pot to repay the flash loan and keep the res=
t for yourself =E2=80=94=C2=A0all at once. And so someone did.=C2=A0</p><p =
style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again: You could do exactly this trade with a=C2=
=A0<em>bank</em>, instead of a stablecoin, if banks were stupidly designed.=
 But they are not!</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[8] This is=C2=A0obv=
ious to banking people but perhaps not to everyone: The way a bank works is=
 that it takes deposits (and owes money back to depositors) and uses them t=
o make loans, buy bonds, etc. A bank with $10 billion of assets might have =
$9 billion of deposits and $1 billion of equity value. It has $10 billion o=
f stuff, it owes $9 billion back to depositors, so there=E2=80=99s $1 billi=
on left over, which belongs to its shareholders.=C2=A0The point is just tha=
t banks are very *leveraged*; they fund most of their assets with deposits,=
 so the assets are worth way more than the equity value of the bank. JPMorg=
an Chase &amp; Co. has a market capitalization of about $370 billion.</em><=
/p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><em>[9] Among other things because they don=
=E2=80=99t keep the deposits in cash in the vaults, etc., though that is no=
t actually as big an obstacle as it seems. The trick is to sell the bank=E2=
=80=99s $10 billion of assets, lend the $10 billion to yourself instead, an=
d use it to buy yachts. That trick also does not work, though, usually.</em=
></p><table class=3D"liveintent-flex-ad" border=3D"0" cellpadding=3D"0" cel=
